post_text:
Congratulations on your retirement Mr. Dan Mattie! Mr. Mattie has been in education for 48 years, 47 of which were with the Voorhees Township School District. He started his career in Voorhees as an eighth-grade English Language Arts teacher. He was promoted and served as the first VMS vice principal until moving into his current role as Director of Program Development. In addition, he served as interim principal of VMS, Kresson School, and Signal Hill School.

Dan Mattie, Voorhees Township Public Schools can not thank you enough for the influence and impact you have had on the students, staff and teachers! Congratulations, you will be missed!

VMS Room A16, one last visit today!!!

shared_text:
Voorhees Breakfast Rotary Club
July 28 at 7:49 AM ¬∑

REMINDER: Summer Free Lunch Distribution Tomorrow

Our summer breakfast/lunch aid program for families with children in the Voorhees, Gibbsboro, Stratford and Lindenwold area will take place tomorrow at 4:30 pm

Day/Time: Each Wednesday 4:30-5:30 pm through August 26.

Meals: Parents may pick up packages of five breakfasts and lunches per child at no charge.

Pickup Location: Our pickup site is the field next to 111 N. Carlton Street in Lindenwold (corner of E. Maple Avenue and N. Carlton Street). Note: For those who remember it, this is the site of the old Moby Dick restaurant.

Social Distance will be maintained: Just drive up and volunteers will help you without you having to exit your car.

Distribution is on a first-come/first-served basis, while supplies last.

If you have questions, please email Glenn Page, Voorhees Breakfast Rotary Club President, at glennpage@comcast.net

post_text:
In September, Shari Kauffman (tech specialist VMS) shared some cyber security contest information with Dr. Rossi. The contest was sponsored by the Multi-State Information Sharing and Analysis Center (MS-ISAC). They both believed the contest requirements aligned nicely with my course curriculum this year, so it became part of an assignment students were working on.

Out of thousands of entries, just 13 entries were chosen as national winners by the MS-ISAC. An 8th grade student, Zoe Redrow, was selected as one of the winners! Zoe‚Äôs artwork will be featured in the 2021 MS-ISAC nationally circulated calendar, in honor of October as National Cybersecurity Awareness Month! The calendars and posters will be mailed to our school at the start of the new school year.

Congratulations Zoe!!!
#voorheeslearns

Osage Science News...Mrs. Putnam and Mrs. Loutzenhiser hosted a Google Meet with their fourth graders and an anthropologist, Lindsay Barone. They connected with her through the Skype a Scientist program. She spoke on evolution and biological variation. The children were fascinated and they asked wonderful questions. They will be doing an writing activity using the new information they have learned. Mrs. Medolla also attended and asked some riveting questions.

post_text:
Our amazing VMS students have participated in our VMS "Thank You" Project to thank our community's health care workers. Rachel Lewis and Alexis Flynn asked the language arts teachers to ask their students to create thank you notes, draw pictures, make inspirational signs, and record thank you videos. Our students did a fantastic job of creating heartfelt messages! We put the submissions together on a Google Slides, and Rachel worked her magic to make it into a video with music and outstanding edits! We will be sending this to Virtua, Jefferson, and their many sites. The video is long, but please take a minute to see your students' hard work! I would like to thank all teachers who helped make this possible, our wonderful VMS students, and Rachel for making this all come together!
#voorheeslearns
https://drive.google.com/file/d/1VptiULTdV6za6WadN4ohsg-LPEkHAYOM/view

CONGRATULATIONS, Osage teacher, Ashley McMichael was chosen to be part of the amazing initiative with NJTV that partners with the NJDOE and the NJEA: a brand new public television program titled NJTV Learning Live.

The program is designed to reach and support remote learning for all New Jersey students, specifically underprivileged children with no internet and/or limited technology access, in grades 3-6. New Jersey teachers will teach 1 hour long lessons from their homes weekdays from 9am-1pm.

Ashley‚Äôs episode is a social studies lesson that will teach NJ students all about New Jersey's regions. She is incredibly excited and proud to represent Voorhees and Osage School. It is slated to air on the PBS channel called NJTV Wednesday, April 15th at 10am
#voorheeslearns

post_text:
Throughout the year, students have been learning about different career choices. This week, our art teacher Shannon Alonzo, inspired us to focus on architecture. Students were able to learn all about architecture through an online video. The students were then able to put their own ideas about architecture into practice by being asked to find materials to build with including Legos, blocks, cups, boxes, and other architectural items. The results of this assignment were magnificent and the students did a fantastic job in creating their own masterpieces. I was beyond impressed to see how creative all of the projects were. Online learning certainly has its challenges, but I am thankful to see what a positive experience it has been thus far working alongside students and parents to support our efforts in administering the best possible learning experience for each and every student.

-Mrs. Ambrozaitis
#voorheeslearns

It was a great learning experience for all!!
